 :tx/rationale "CCE-5 IMPLEMENTER NOTES (addendum to t-455bbfa1): FALLBACK BEHAVIORS for steering responses. (1) ZERO CONCEPTS (fresh store, first observation): Response is innate-schema-based. 'This observation relates to [components/dependencies/invariants/patterns/anomalies] (innate schema). 0 concepts formed yet. Explore more to discover patterns.' The innate schema match is via embedding cosine against innate concept centroids. (2) ONE CONCEPT (early exploration): No inter-concept steering question possible. Use intra-concept question: 'concept:X has {N} members spanning {packages}. What about {mentioned_entity} isn't covered yet?' Or coverage-based: '{M} of {T} packages explored. Nearest unexplored: {frontier}.' (3) MULTIPLE CONCEPTS: Full steering mode. Concept membership + structural gap + inter-concept question. (4) INNATE SCHEMA FADE: After 10+ observations, if at least 3 emergent concepts exist, stop showing innate schemas in status. Replace with emergent concept inventory. Innate concepts remain in the store (never deleted — C1) but are filtered from the display by checking :concept/innate = true AND emergent_concept_count >= 3. (5) CONCEPT CORRECTION: If agent observes 'this is about error handling, not event processing' after a wrong assignment, the observe pipeline should detect negation patterns ('not X', 'actually Y', 'wrong concept') and treat as a concept reassignment signal. Implementation: check if observation text contains 'not :concept/' or 'actually :concept/' patterns. If detected: retract the :exploration/concept Ref from the wrong concept, assert Ref to the correct concept, update both centroids. This teaches braid to refine boundaries from agent feedback — the ACCOMMODATION step in Piaget's cycle. (6) SURPRISE IN RESPONSE: Per CCE-2b, include surprise magnitude in the response. Low (<0.1): 'Confirms concept:X'. Medium (0.1-0.3): 'Extends concept:X (surprise=0.XX)'. High (>0.3): 'At the edge of concept:X (surprise=0.XX). This may bridge to concept:Y.' This maps exactly to Piaget: assimilation (low surprise), accommodation (high surprise)."
